And if we have any time at the end
of class, I'm not promising...

241
00:21:11,602 --> 00:21:14,322
...because I want us to get
to our breathing exercises...

242
00:21:14,523 --> 00:21:19,075
...but if we have time, we might try
a spiky arrangement or two.

243
00:21:19,284 --> 00:21:24,040
But first we're gonna start by doing
a little work treating our stems.

244
00:21:24,245 --> 00:21:27,955
And we're gonna start by working
with our woody stems...

245
00:21:28,166 --> 00:21:33,719
...because they can be a little on the
tricky side and require the most TLC.

246
00:21:33,927 --> 00:21:35,645
Tough loving care.

247
00:21:36,527 --> 00:21:40,601
Okay, let's start with an azalea,
one of my favorites.

248
00:21:41,008 --> 00:21:44,445
Starting an inch or two
from the bottom of the stem...

249
00:21:44,649 --> 00:21:47,369
...and if it's a thick stem,
we really have to smash them...

250
00:21:47,570 --> 00:21:50,607
...we split the stem vertically.

251
00:21:50,810 --> 00:21:53,928
Does anyone know why we do this?

252
00:21:54,451 --> 00:21:58,127
Anyone? Yes.

253
00:21:58,572 --> 00:22:01,531
- So it will draw more water?
- Very good.

254
00:22:01,733 --> 00:22:05,726
Did everyone hear that?
So it will draw more water.

255
00:22:05,934 --> 00:22:11,089
Okay. Does everyone have
their hammers? Let's begin.

256
00:22:27,778 --> 00:22:29,257
You're supposed to be in bed.

257
00:22:29,458 --> 00:22:31,609
I needed to get some turkey franks
and milk for Julio.

258
00:22:31,819 --> 00:22:34,573
Why didn't you call me? I could've
stopped home on my way from work.

259
00:22:34,780 --> 00:22:37,374
- He has a snack at 3:30.
- Why didn't you call your sister?

260
00:22:38,580 --> 00:22:41,015
She just got two days
on a new Nicolas Cage movie.

261
00:22:41,221 --> 00:22:43,975
She plays this hooker who witnesses
a murder, then gets raped and killed.

262
00:22:44,182 --> 00:22:47,492
She's got lines and everything! She
wants me to come visit her on the set.

263
00:22:47,702 --> 00:22:48,772
Well, you're supposed to be in bed.

264
00:22:48,983 --> 00:22:51,543
I got bored and went to the market.
What's the big deal?

265
00:22:51,743 --> 00:22:54,338
- What are you doing home anyway?
- I came home for lunch.

266
00:22:54,544 --> 00:22:57,820
- I was worried.
- Rico, please. I'm fine.

267
00:22:58,024 --> 00:22:59,856
I'm not just worried about you.

268
00:23:02,225 --> 00:23:05,741
Okay.
This is about the baby at work.

269
00:23:06,346 --> 00:23:08,736
I just...
I can't do it.

270
00:23:09,307 --> 00:23:12,265
Of course you can.

271
00:23:16,428 --> 00:23:18,420
He looks like...

272
00:23:18,629 --> 00:23:20,665
Like he's sleeping.

273
00:23:20,869 --> 00:23:24,067
Like a baby who's fallen asleep.

274
00:23:24,270 --> 00:23:29,903
He was 3 weeks old.
There was nothing wrong with him.

275
00:23:30,311 --> 00:23:33,588
And then, just like that...

276
00:23:33,792 --> 00:23:35,987
...he dies.

277
00:23:36,633 --> 00:23:39,101
For no reason.

278
00:23:39,833 --> 00:23:41,506
How can that be?

279
00:23:41,714 --> 00:23:46,391
How can the beginning and end
be so damn close together?

280
00:23:48,635 --> 00:23:52,549
And now I've got this real bad feeling.

281
00:23:54,076 --> 00:23:57,387
I haven't done a baby
since Julio was born.

282
00:23:57,597 --> 00:23:59,986
David always does them.

283
00:24:02,078 --> 00:24:07,676
- So make David do this one.
- David's in Vegas until tomorrow.

284
00:24:07,879 --> 00:24:10,758
The viewing is this afternoon.

285
00:24:15,201 --> 00:24:19,514
Some babies just aren't meant
for this world, Rico.

286
00:24:21,082 --> 00:24:23,642
But this one is.

287
00:24:34,405 --> 00:24:36,202
Turn to page seven
in your notebooks...

288
00:24:36,405 --> 00:24:38,681
...we'll go step by step
through the most challenging...

289
00:24:38,886 --> 00:24:43,324
...cranial facial reconstruction
I ever faced.

290
00:24:43,527 --> 00:24:45,995
If we could go to
the next slide, please.

291
00:24:49,208 --> 00:24:52,200
- Oh, my God.
- Oh, Jesus.

292
00:24:52,929 --> 00:24:57,446
- That shit is fucked up.
- Nate, this is Chloe Yorkin.

293
00:24:57,650 --> 00:25:00,722
The job Federico left us
to do for Kroehner?

294
00:25:00,930 --> 00:25:03,206
Oh, God.
That is like fucking science fiction.

295
00:25:05,171 --> 00:25:08,323
The first question my team
and I asked ourselves was not...

296
00:25:08,532 --> 00:25:11,330
...as it might have been at a
facility with less resources...

297
00:25:11,532 --> 00:25:15,367
...can we do this?
- They don't even credit Rico by name.

298
00:25:15,573 --> 00:25:18,646
Oh, man, he's gonna be furious.

299
00:25:24,015 --> 00:25:25,812
Oh, God.

300
00:25:26,016 --> 00:25:28,166
Well, that is a very generous
offer, Roger...

301
00:25:28,376 --> 00:25:32,211
...but unfortunately I am in a relationship
at the moment. If I was...

302
00:25:32,417 --> 00:25:34,612
Deal me in.

303
00:25:36,298 --> 00:25:38,687
Jesus, Billy.

304
00:25:38,898 --> 00:25:41,936
Hold on. Hey!
So where's your boyfriend?

305
00:25:42,139 --> 00:25:44,573
What are you doing here?

306
00:25:44,819 --> 00:25:46,538
I love Vegas.
You know I love Vegas.

307
00:25:46,740 --> 00:25:50,256
And sometimes when my sister isn't
there when I need her, I hop in my car...

308
00:25:50,461 --> 00:25:52,850
...start driving, wind up here.
- Billy, you're lying.

309
00:25:53,061 --> 00:25:55,530
I'm really not.
I just saw you at the blackjack table.

310
00:25:55,742 --> 00:25:57,812
- It was a total coincidence.
- You're a fucking liar.

311
00:25:58,022 --> 00:26:01,572
You're a selfish, manipulative,
narcissistic liar.

312
00:26:04,864 --> 00:26:09,700
- What did Mom and Dad tell you?
- They told me that you made a bomb.

313
00:26:11,745 --> 00:26:15,534
That's fucking hilarious.
So now I'm like, what, a terrorist?

314
00:26:15,746 --> 00:26:17,862
"Billy Mc Veigh"?

315
00:26:20,027 --> 00:26:21,938
They're fucking liars, Brenda!

316
00:26:22,147 --> 00:26:25,106
They hate each other and they're
miserable and they're jealous of us...

317
00:26:25,308 --> 00:26:27,583
...and they want us to hate
each other too. So they lie to us!

318
00:26:27,788 --> 00:26:31,020
No, they lied to me, you lied to me. You
let me believe you tried to kill yourself.

319
00:26:31,229 --> 00:26:32,378
Do you know how fucked that is?

320
00:26:32,589 --> 00:26:34,899
You know what?
I was so fucking drugged up...

321
00:26:35,110 --> 00:26:36,828
...I don't even really
remember what happened.

322
00:26:37,030 --> 00:26:38,908
Dad showed me what you wrote.

323
00:26:44,152 --> 00:26:46,268
I was kidding, okay?

324
00:26:47,033 --> 00:26:49,672
It wasn't serious.

325
00:26:50,273 --> 00:26:54,392
Do you have any idea
what I gave up for you?

326
00:26:54,594 --> 00:26:57,712
Because I thought that if you tried
to kill yourself again and succeeded...

327
00:26:57,915 --> 00:27:00,873
...I could tell myself that I did
everything I could to save you.

328
00:27:01,075 --> 00:27:02,509
And you did.

329
00:27:03,396 --> 00:27:06,628
- You've saved me every day since then.
- Well, fuck you!

330
00:27:06,837 --> 00:27:09,874
- Brenda, don't fucking walk away...
- I'm having a life. Just back off!

331
00:27:10,077 --> 00:27:12,353
Hey, you heard her! Now, fuck off!

332
00:27:17,519 --> 00:27:19,635
Nice.

333
00:27:25,081 --> 00:27:27,197
Are you okay?

334
00:27:27,961 --> 00:27:30,601
He followed us here.

335
00:27:32,282 --> 00:27:36,276
I hate to say it,
but I'm not entirely surprised.

336
00:28:13,651 --> 00:28:16,119
Very nice.

337
00:28:16,731 --> 00:28:19,121
Luscious.

338
00:28:22,413 --> 00:28:24,005
This is a little...

339
00:28:24,213 --> 00:28:25,566
...tight.

340
00:28:25,773 --> 00:28:29,323
- Tight?
- You're not breathing right.

341
00:28:29,534 --> 00:28:32,288
- I'm not?
- You're breathing from here...

342
00:28:32,495 --> 00:28:35,089
...when you should be
breathing from here.

343
00:28:35,295 --> 00:28:37,332
- But my lungs are here.
- Of course they are.

344
00:28:37,536 --> 00:28:39,413
I'm speaking metaphorically.

345
00:28:39,616 --> 00:28:42,973
If you breathe from up here, your
arrangements will come from up here.

346
00:28:43,177 --> 00:28:47,808
If you breathe from down here, your
arrangements will come from down here.

347
00:28:48,018 --> 00:28:50,578
- And that's good?
- That's very good.

348
00:28:50,778 --> 00:28:52,531
- Do you do yoga?
- No.

349
00:28:52,739 --> 00:28:55,971
Okay. Would everybody grab
a yoga mat in the next room?

350
00:28:56,180 --> 00:29:00,857
We're gonna do some breathing
exercises before we break for dinner.

351
00:29:02,581 --> 00:29:04,970
You're a bit of a control freak,
aren't you?

352
00:29:05,182 --> 00:29:08,015
No, I'm not. I don't think I am.

353
00:29:08,222 --> 00:29:09,541
- Am I?
- Yes.

354
00:29:09,742 --> 00:29:12,576
And control freaks
do not make good arrangers.

355
00:29:12,783 --> 00:29:15,503
Believe me, I know.
I used to be a control freak too.

356
00:29:15,944 --> 00:29:18,412
But you know what?
You can get over it.

357
00:29:18,624 --> 00:29:21,378
All you have to do is learn to breathe.

358
00:29:21,785 --> 00:29:24,220
- Are you on antidepressants?
- No!

359
00:29:24,426 --> 00:29:27,975
Well, Lord knows I'd be lost
without my Saint John's Wort.

360
00:29:31,427 --> 00:29:35,467
There are countless challenges facing
independent funeral homes today:

361
00:29:35,668 --> 00:29:39,548
Changing social attitudes
toward death and dying...

362
00:29:39,749 --> 00:29:44,540
...economic hardship in communities
both large and small...

363
00:30:00,913 --> 00:30:03,382
Oh, what the hell.

364
00:30:04,914 --> 00:30:08,464
We all know what the real challenge is.

365
00:30:10,995 --> 00:30:13,874
How are you doing today, Mr. Gilardi?

366
00:30:14,476 --> 00:30:17,628
- Fine, thank you.
- Glad to hear it.

367
00:30:18,397 --> 00:30:20,911
We all know of a certain organization...

368
00:30:21,117 --> 00:30:24,155
...that controls the flow
of prep-room supplies...

369
00:30:24,358 --> 00:30:30,070
...caskets, cemetery property and
flowers to everyone in this room.

370
00:30:30,279 --> 00:30:32,840
And believe me, that organization
will stoop to almost any means...

371
00:30:33,040 --> 00:30:35,508
...to make sure that the independent
funeral home has no future.

372
00:30:35,721 --> 00:30:37,074
But hear me out.

373
00:30:38,881 --> 00:30:42,272
My father was in this business
for over 35 years.

374
00:30:42,482 --> 00:30:44,120
He...

375
00:30:44,922 --> 00:30:48,632
He thought it was okay to tell people
about a cheaper casket.

376
00:30:48,843 --> 00:30:51,836
He didn't always try
to talk people out of cremation.

377
00:30:52,044 --> 00:30:54,239
There were even times
where I actually heard him say:

378
00:30:54,444 --> 00:30:56,754
"To hell with our profit margin on this."

379
00:30:57,605 --> 00:31:00,166
These words are heresy
to a certain organization...

380
00:31:00,366 --> 00:31:01,958
...because profit is all it cares about...

381
00:31:02,166 --> 00:31:05,842
...no matter how many PR-motivated
seminars it sponsors.

382
00:31:06,047 --> 00:31:08,197
That organization wants us
independents to believe...

383
00:31:08,407 --> 00:31:10,797
...that we cannot afford to be
like my father anymore.

384
00:31:11,008 --> 00:31:12,726
Well, I'm sorry, but that's bullshit.

385
00:31:12,928 --> 00:31:15,762
Don't get me wrong, my father
worried about the bottom line too...

386
00:31:15,969 --> 00:31:18,437
...but he worried more
about other things.

387
00:31:18,650 --> 00:31:20,561
Like comforting people...

388
00:31:20,770 --> 00:31:23,125
...and helping them face profound loss.

389
00:31:26,011 --> 00:31:31,370
Maybe now more than ever, we should
all try to be a little more like him.

390
00:31:33,333 --> 00:31:34,812
Thank you.

391
00:32:01,819 --> 00:32:04,379
- Very motivational.
- Good job.

392
00:32:05,579 --> 00:32:07,013
How'd I do?

393
00:32:07,220 --> 00:32:11,260
Are you kidding? You kicked
some serious ass, you big freak.

394
00:32:16,782 --> 00:32:19,819
You didn't come home last night.

395
00:32:20,823 --> 00:32:23,815
Well, it's not like it was a school night.

396
00:32:24,623 --> 00:32:27,502
Would you like me to
make you something to eat?

397
00:32:27,704 --> 00:32:30,139
Yeah, that'd be great.

398
00:32:36,946 --> 00:32:39,984
Do you think I'm a control freak?

399
00:32:41,187 --> 00:32:43,337
Yeah.

400
00:32:44,428 --> 00:32:49,184
- Where do you think David gets it from?
- Your father was very controlling.

401
00:32:49,389 --> 00:32:52,187
- Not like you.
- That's not nice.

402
00:32:52,669 --> 00:32:53,658
You asked.

403
00:32:57,670 --> 00:33:00,708
You're not as bad as you used to be.

404
00:33:01,671 --> 00:33:04,789
May I ask where you were all night?

405
00:33:05,752 --> 00:33:08,027
In Barstow.

406
00:33:08,233 --> 00:33:10,349
What in God's name
were you doing there?

407
00:33:10,553 --> 00:33:12,623
I was visiting a friend of mine
who's in the hospital.

408
00:33:12,833 --> 00:33:14,665
Who?

409
00:33:15,234 --> 00:33:17,702
Gabriel Dimas.

410
00:33:18,635 --> 00:33:22,629
- The young man whose brother...
- Yeah.

411
00:33:24,756 --> 00:33:27,510
What was he doing in the hospital?

412
00:33:28,677 --> 00:33:29,996
He OD'd.

413
00:33:31,117 --> 00:33:33,757
Good Lord.

414
00:33:35,598 --> 00:33:37,715
Claire...

415
00:33:38,559 --> 00:33:42,075
...he's obviously a deeply disturbed boy.

416
00:33:42,280 --> 00:33:46,832
You need to steer clear of him.
Let his family deal with this.

417
00:33:47,041 --> 00:33:50,954
Well, let's take stock
for a second, shall we?

418
00:33:52,282 --> 00:33:54,921
His little brother's dead.
His father's dead.

419
00:33:55,242 --> 00:33:57,074
His stepfather beat him up...

420
00:33:57,283 --> 00:34:01,163
...his white-trash mother who smokes
like a fish could give a shit.

421
00:34:01,364 --> 00:34:04,003
That leaves no one.

422
00:34:05,004 --> 00:34:08,315
Was his overdose an accident?

423
00:34:08,525 --> 00:34:12,041
- Of course it was an accident.
- Because sometimes these things aren't.

424
00:34:12,246 --> 00:34:16,320
And if it wasn't, it could happen again.
There's an 80%/% chance that someone...

425
00:34:16,527 --> 00:34:19,166
It wasn't a suicide attempt.

426
00:34:19,367 --> 00:34:21,518
I hope, for his sake, you're right.

427
00:34:22,528 --> 00:34:25,407
But if you're wrong, Claire...

428
00:34:25,689 --> 00:34:29,079
I don't want you
getting too close to him.

429
00:34:38,852 --> 00:34:40,205
- Thank you.
- No problem.

430
00:34:40,412 --> 00:34:42,050
Look at him.

431
00:34:42,932 --> 00:34:45,163
- He's a star.
- Hi. Really great.

432
00:34:45,613 --> 00:34:48,606
I just want you guys to meet someone.

433
00:34:49,454 --> 00:34:54,131
This is my brother and partner
Nathaniel Jr. And his...

434
00:34:55,255 --> 00:34:58,328
- Jasmine.
- Hey, there, I'm Neil Schaeger.

435
00:34:58,536 --> 00:35:00,572
- Schaeger and Sons, from Flagstaff.
- Raymond Dooley.

436
00:35:00,776 --> 00:35:03,086
Dooley and Moss Funeral Home,
Reno, Nevada.

437
00:35:03,297 --> 00:35:05,447
Moss couldn't be here. Bladder cancer.

438
00:35:05,977 --> 00:35:07,934
That was a hell of a speech
David made.

439
00:35:08,138 --> 00:35:11,130
Almost made me cry when those
Kroehner bastards got up and left.

440
00:35:11,338 --> 00:35:15,014
Those fuckers have been trying
to buy us out for five goddamn years.

441
00:35:15,219 --> 00:35:17,336
Your father was a good man.

442
00:35:17,780 --> 00:35:18,735
Yes, he was.

443
00:35:18,980 --> 00:35:21,619
Y'all don't mind if we drag your
little brother out with us, do you?

444
00:35:21,821 --> 00:35:24,540
- I really shouldn't.
- Gotta let us buy you a drink at least.

445
00:35:24,741 --> 00:35:26,733
- You're our hero.
- Well, maybe just a quick one.

446
00:35:26,942 --> 00:35:29,251
Quick one, my Aunt Fanny.
We're gonna make a night of it.

447
00:35:29,462 --> 00:35:31,340
Hey, you want to go with?
The more the merrier.

448
00:35:32,343 --> 00:35:36,383
Oh, I don't think so.
We're just gonna lay low tonight.

449
00:35:36,584 --> 00:35:41,579
- Yeah, but you guys have fun.
- Okay, your loss.

450
00:36:00,629 --> 00:36:01,982
Excuse me.

451
00:36:03,109 --> 00:36:05,749
We'd just like to thank you...

452
00:36:06,310 --> 00:36:08,983
...very much.
- He looks so beautiful.

453
00:36:09,190 --> 00:36:10,783
I'm glad you're pleased.

454
00:36:10,991 --> 00:36:13,107
Mike's mom and dad
drove down from Salinas.

455
00:36:13,311 --> 00:36:17,988
Yeah. They never got
a chance to meet him.

456
00:36:18,192 --> 00:36:21,788
Now it's almost like they did.

457
00:36:22,713 --> 00:36:27,310
- Do you have children?
- Yes. Yes, I do.

458
00:36:27,514 --> 00:36:33,273
I have a 4-year-old boy and my...

459
00:36:33,476 --> 00:36:34,829
